{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17655859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17655859"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:07:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:07:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18690"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18690"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11422"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76851"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11422"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18690"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62356"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10312"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26451"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26460"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76851","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76851"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESympathetic ganglia are collections of nerve cell bodies located in the paravertebral chain that relay signals from the central nervous system to target organs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes neurotransmission at sympathetic ganglia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dopamine binding to dopaminergic receptors","Noradrenaline binding to beta receptors","Acetylcholine binding to muscarinic receptors","Acetylcholine binding to nicotinic receptors","Noradrenaline binding to alpha receptors"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct mechanism involves \u003Cstrong\u003Eacetylcholine binding to nicotinic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E. Preganglionic sympathetic neurons release acetylcholine which binds to nicotinic acetylcholine receptors on postganglionic neurons within the sympathetic ganglia. This produces fast excitatory postsynaptic potentials through ion channel opening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENoradrenaline binding to alpha receptors\u003C/strong\u003E - While noradrenaline is released by postganglionic neurons at target organs, it is not the neurotransmitter within sympathetic ganglia\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcetylcholine binding to muscarinic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E - Although acetylcholine is the correct neurotransmitter, muscarinic receptors are not found in significant numbers in sympathetic ganglia\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENoradrenaline binding to beta receptors\u003C/strong\u003E - Noradrenaline acts at target organs, not within the ganglia themselves\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDopamine binding to dopaminergic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E - Dopamine is not involved in normal ganglionic transmission\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter the ganglionic synapse, the postganglionic sympathetic neurons then primarily use noradrenaline as their neurotransmitter to affect target organs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sympathetic ganglia contain nicotinic acetylcholine receptors that mediate fast synaptic transmission between preganglionic and postganglionic neurons.","Preganglionic sympathetic neurons release acetylcholine as their neurotransmitter.","Postganglionic sympathetic neurons primarily release noradrenaline at their target organs."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62356"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18690"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62356","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62356"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T14:15:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T14:16:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11422"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76851"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16: